HJR11 Enrolled
1 Enrolled, An Act,
2
3 RECOGNIZING NOVEMBER 2026 AS DIABETES MONTH IN THE STATE OF
4 ALABAMA.
5
6 WHEREAS, in Alabama, more than 553,000 individuals
7 are living with diabetes, and an estimated 1.3 million
8 individuals, representing 34.6 percent of the adult
9 population, have prediabetes, a condition that significantly
10 increases the risk of developing Type 2 diabetes; and
11 WHEREAS, the lifetime risk of developing Type 2
12 diabetes is approximately 40 percent for adults in the
13 United States; and each year an estimated 41,000 adults in
14 Alabama are newly diagnosed with diabetes; and
15 WHEREAS, diabetes is a serious chronic condition that
16 affects individuals of every age, race, ethnicity, and
17 income level; and, as of November 2025, a cure for diabetes
18 does not exist; and
19 WHEREAS, the Centers for Disease Control and
20 Prevention reports that Hispanic, Black, Asian, American
21 Indian, and Alaska Native Adults in the United States are
22 disproportionately affected by diabetes and develop the
23 disease at a significantly higher rate than the general
24 population; and
25 WHEREAS, Type 1 diabetes accounts for about 10
26 percent of all diabetes cases, meaning that roughly
27 60,000-70,000 Alabamians are likely live with Type 1
28 diabetes, which is often diagnosed in childhood or young
Page 1

diabetes, which is often diagnosed in childhood or young
HJR11 Enrolled
29 adulthood; and
30 WHEREAS, research demonstrates a rising trend in Type
31 1 diabetes diagnoses among Alabama's youth; and this disease
32 places a significant burden on individuals and families due
33 to serious health risks, making it a major public health
34 concern in the state; and
35 WHEREAS, individuals with diabetes incur medical
36 expenses that are approximately 2.6 times higher than those
37 without diabetes; and the American Diabetes Association
38 reports that, in 2022, care for individuals with diagnosed
39 diabetes accounted for one in four health care dollars spent
40 in the United States; and
41 WHEREAS, evidence-based strategies exist to reduce
42 the incidence of Type 2 diabetes and to delay or prevent its
43 onset; and
44 WHEREAS, with proper education, management, and
45 treatment, individuals with diabetes live healthy,
46 productive, and fulfilling lives; and
47 WHEREAS, individuals throughout the United States
48 observe American Diabetes Month in November; and
49 WHEREAS, the Legislature of Alabama is committed to
50 celebrating the resilience and courage of individuals and
51 families affected by diabetes; and
52 WHEREAS, we express our gratitude to the dedicated
53 medical professionals, caregivers, loved ones, and advocates
54 who support and serve the diabetes community; and
55 WHEREAS, during the month of November, we encourage
56 all Alabamians, school systems, nonprofit organizations,
Page 2

all Alabamians, school systems, nonprofit organizations,
HJR11 Enrolled
57 health care providers, and other interested groups to engage
58 in activities that promote diabetes awareness and support
59 the prevention, treatment, and management of this disease;
60 now therefore,
61 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA, BOTH
62 HOUSES THEREOF CONCURRING, That November 2026 is declared to
63 be Diabetes Month in the State of Alabama, and its
64 observance is hereby commended to all residents.
